post_text: For today‚Äôs Team Tulsa Tuesday, we would like to introduce you to Khalilah Jones! Khalilah serves as the site-based social worker at East Central High School and has been a member of Team Tulsa for three years. Prior to joining the East Central High School family, she served as a paraprofessional from 2005-2008, where she discovered her interest in public education. As social worker at East Central, Khalilah provides resources and referrals to students and families, works to eliminate barriers to students‚Äô social and emotional needs, provides crisis and case management, and serves as the school‚Äôs homeless liaison as well as the site coordinator for the Tulsa Campaign to Prevent Teen Pregnancy. Khalilah is grateful for her East Central family and amazing colleagues and advises new district employees to ‚Äúmaximize every opportunity and use it for growth, while staying true to yourself and your path.‚Äù Thank you, Khalilah, for being a part of our team and for everything that you do for our students!!

We are excited to announce that we‚Äôve partnered with the U.S. Census Bureau to support the #2020Census! Here are some ways you can verify an individual is a Census Bureau employee:

‚Ä¢The census taker or field representative will present an ID badge that includes:
-their name,
-their photograph,
-a Department of Commerce watermark, and
-an expiration date.
‚Ä¢They will have an official bag and Census Bureau-issued electronic device, such as a laptop or smartphone, bearing the Census Bureau logo.
‚Ä¢Census takers and field representatives will conduct their work between the hours of 9 a.m. and 9 p.m., local time.
‚Ä¢Census representatives will be at local organizations and community events with computer tablets to help individuals respond online to the 2020 Census.

The best way to avoid being visited at home by a census taker, or enumerator, is to complete the 2020 Census online, by phone, or by mail. Learn more here:
https://2020census.gov/es/news-events/rumors/home-affairs-hoax.html

post_text: Happy Team Tulsa Tuesday! Today, we would like you to meet Mario Jones, fatherhood coordinator for our Strong Tomorrows program. Mario has been with Tulsa Public Schools since 2017 and works with expecting and parenting students in the district. The motto for Strong Tomorrows Fatherhood is ‚ÄúBetter Men, Better Students, Better Fathers,‚Äù so he works with his students by helping to monitor grades, attendance, behavior, and by providing mentorship on topics like communication, creating healthy relationships, and parenting skills. Mario enjoys being out and about in schools and in the community. His favorite part about his role is being able to meet the needs of the students he serves in any setting, saying ‚ÄúI‚Äôve had the pleasure to meet some awesome people and work with a great team.‚Äù Outside of work, Mario loves football and investing time into being a great husband and father to his own family. We are so grateful for the important work that you do and are glad to have you on our team!

We love our students and team and are deeply dedicated to keeping everyone safe and well. Team Tulsa continues to work with health and safety experts to stay updated on the status and spread of coronavirus/COVID-19.

While this situation is changing by the hour, our most current information is as follows:

‚Ä¢ To slow the spread COVID-19 in our community, all schools in our district will be closed through Friday, April 3. At this time, students will return to classes no earlier than Monday, April 6. Families should anticipate that there may be an even longer closure.
‚Ä¢ District office buildings will be open Tuesday, March 17. Beginning on Wednesday, March 18, district buildings will be closed until Friday, April 3.

We will continue to share information and updates through email, text message, and on our website at www.tulsaschools.org/coronavirus. You can also sign-up for text message alerts from Tulsa Public Schools by texting ‚ÄúYES‚Äù to 67587.
